                text = "*(He is achingly young — for an elf, barely more than a boy — and he wears the junior robes of the court with a pride that has not yet learned to be anything else. You know this face. You have seen it ten thousand years older, carrying a grief so deep it has its own gravity. But *here*, *now*, the eyes are *clear* and *certain* and entirely without the wound, and Ilfaeril the Younger straightens as you approach, eager to be taken seriously.)* You're observing the founding? *(brightly.)* Then you're witnessing *history.* The Coronal's mercy-sentence — the Wall. I'm to cast a *junior vote.* My *first.* *(he cannot quite hide his pride.)* My elders say I have the clearest legal mind of my generation. I intend to prove them right. I've studied the sentence from every angle, and it is *flawless.* I shall vote *yes* with a *whole heart.*",
                autoNextNodeId = "1",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "npc.young_ilfaeril_met", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act3.crown_wars_witnessed", op = FlagOp.SetTrue } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "1", speaker = "Ilfaeril, the Younger",
                text = "*(He lays out his reasoning with the crisp, joyful confidence of a brilliant young man who has never yet been *wrong* about anything that mattered.)* Here is the elegance of it. *(he ticks the points off, alight.)* The faithless cannot be *claimed* by gods — fact. Unclaimed, they *annihilate* — fact. Annihilation is *irreversible* and therefore *maximally* cruel — fact. The Wall *preserves* — therefore the Wall is *less* cruel than the alternative — therefore the Wall is the *merciful* choice — therefore a *just* judge *must* vote for it. *(he beams.)* It's *airtight.* I've checked it a hundred times. *(then he pauses, and the first faint shadow — the one that will become his whole long life — crosses his clear young face.)* The only... the only piece I can't quite *close* is — well. The sentence assumes that *being kept* is *better* than *being nothing.* And I've *proven* that *logically*, but I keep — *(he frowns)* — I keep wanting to *ask* one of the faithless whether *they* agree, and my elders say that's *sentimental*, that the *logic* settles it, that a judge who needs the *defendant's* opinion isn't a judge but a — a *coward.* *(he looks at you, the certainty wobbling for just a heartbeat.)* It *is* airtight. Isn't it? The logic. ...You've been around. Tell me it's airtight. I vote within the hour.",
                choices = new[]
                {
                    new DialogueChoice { text = "[INSIGHT 18] \"It's airtight because you built it out of *facts* and left out the one thing that isn't a fact — what it's *like* to be kept. You can't close it with logic because the hole in it is *experiential.* Go to the dock. Ask Maerys. Then vote.\"", nextNodeId = "ask", checkAbility = Ability.Wisdom, checkDC = 18, failNodeId = "loyal" },
                    new DialogueChoice { text = "\"I know how this vote ends, Ilfaeril, because I've met *you* — ten thousand years from now, still carrying it. The clear mind you're so proud of is about to make the one error it spends an *age* trying to forgive. *Don't raise your hand.*\"", nextNodeId = "future", failNodeId = "loyal" },
                    new DialogueChoice { text = "\"Your elders call asking the defendant 'cowardice.' Flip it. The coward is the judge who hides behind *airtight logic* so he never has to *feel* the face he's condemning. Courage is asking the question that might *unmake* your proof.\"", nextNodeId = "courage" },
                    new DialogueChoice { text = "\"Vote however your conscience lands — but cast it having *looked* at her. Whatever you decide, decide it to Maerys's *face*, not to a syllogism. Owe her that much. Owe *yourself* that much.\"", nextNodeId = "face", effects = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "companion.ilfaeril.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 3 } } },
                }
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "ask", speaker = "Ilfaeril, the Younger",
                text = "*(The young judge goes still, and the airtight certainty develops, for the first time in his life, a *crack* — the very crack you have watched the elder Ilfaeril carry for ten thousand years.)* The hole is *experiential.* *(slowly.)* I built the proof out of *facts* and the missing piece *isn't* one. *(he looks toward the dock, toward Maerys, and something in his clear young face begins — just begins — to be afraid.)* My elders said the *logic settles it.* But logic can only settle what it can *measure*, and I *cannot measure* what ten thousand years in the grey *feels like* — I *assumed* it was better than nothing because *I* would rather *exist* than not, but — *(his voice drops)* — but I have never been *kept against my will for an age.* I'm *guessing.* I dressed a *guess* in a *syllogism* and called it *justice.* *(he stares at his own young hand — the hand that is meant to rise in a vote.)* If I go to the dock... if I *ask* her... and she says *\"I would rather be nothing than be kept\"* — then my airtight proof *shatters*, and I'll have to vote *no*, and *defy* the Coronal, and *fail* my elders, and throw away the brilliant career they've promised me on my *first vote* — *(he looks at you, terrified and awake.)* — or I *don't* ask, and I vote *yes* in *comfortable ignorance*, and stay *brilliant*, and *certain*, and *clean.* *(quietly.)* You've shown me that the whole sentence rests on a question I've been *forbidden* to ask. I think — gods, I think I have to ask it. Even if it costs me *everything.* Where is she? Where is the first of the faithless? I need to *ask* before I can *raise my hand.*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "npc.young_ilfaeril_doubts", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act3.ilfaeril_asks", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act1.mercy_remembered", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "companion.ilfaeril.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 6 } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "future", speaker = "Ilfaeril, the Younger",
                text = "*(He stares at you, and the young certainty fractures into something between terror and yearning.)* You've *met* me. *(barely a whisper.)* Ten thousand years — *(his hand drifts to his chest.)* You're saying I — that I *do* vote yes. That I *raise my hand.* And that I spend an *age* — *(his voice shakes)* — *carrying* it. *(he searches your face.)* Then it *isn't* airtight. Because a *correct* vote doesn't leave a *wound* you carry for ten thousand years. A *just* act doesn't — doesn't *haunt* the man who did it across an entire *age.* *(he's trembling now.)* My elder self. Is he — am I — *(he can barely ask)* — am I *sorry?* Ten thousand years from now? Do I *regret* the hand I'm about to raise? *(and whatever he reads in your silence answers him.)* ...I do. *(quietly, devastated, and finally *wise* in a way the brilliant boy was not.)* Then the future is *begging* the past not to. And the past — *(he looks at his hand)* — the past is *me*, *right now*, *still able to choose.* *(he closes his hand into a fist, lowering it.)* I won't raise it. I don't *understand* what it costs yet — you do, the old me does — but I *trust* the grief you're describing more than I trust my own *airtight* pride. *(he meets your eyes, young and resolved.)* Tell my elder self — tell *me* — that the boy *listened.* That this time, the hand stayed *down.* Maybe that changes nothing. Maybe the Wall is built without my vote. But at least the *wound* — at least *this* version doesn't have to carry the *wound.*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "npc.young_ilfaeril_refuses", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act3.ilfaeril_hand_stays_down", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act3.loop_glimpsed", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "companion.ilfaeril.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 6 } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "courage", speaker = "Ilfaeril, the Younger",
                text = "*(He flinches, then leans in, the brilliant mind seizing the reframe.)* The coward hides behind airtight logic. *(slowly.)* So that he never has to *feel* the face. *(he looks toward the dock, stricken.)* My elders taught me that *feeling* is the *enemy* of *judgment* — that a great judge is *cold*, *clean*, *unmoved.* And I was so *proud* to be *cold* at *eighteen.* *(his voice tightens.)* But you've turned it over: a judge who *engineers* a proof so *tight* that the *defendant's suffering can't get in* — that judge isn't *brave* and *rigorous.* He's *hiding.* He built the *airtight* logic *precisely so the air — the breath, the face, the* please *— couldn't reach him.* *(he looks at his own hand.)* *Coward* was never the judge who asks. *Coward* was *me*, building a fortress of *therefores* so I'd never have to *look at her.* *(fiercely, young and shaking.)* Then I'll do the *brave* thing. The thing my elders call *weakness.* I'll go to the dock, and I'll *look*, and I'll let her face *into* my airtight proof, and if it *shatters* — *good.* A proof that can't survive *one human face* deserves to shatter. *(he straightens.)* Thank you. You've taught me that *rigor without mercy is just cowardice with footnotes.* I'd rather fail my elders *looking* than satisfy them *blind.*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "npc.young_ilfaeril_courage", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act3.ilfaeril_asks", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "companion.ilfaeril.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 5 } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "face", speaker = "Ilfaeril, the Younger",
                text = "*(He considers this — the gentlest of your challenges, and somehow the hardest.)* Decide it to her *face.* *(quietly.)* Not to the *syllogism.* *(he looks down at the dock, where Maerys waits.)* You're not even telling me how to *vote.* You're only telling me to *look* while I do it. *(he swallows.)* That's — that's somehow *worse* than if you'd argued with me. Because I *can* dismiss an *argument* — I'm *good* at that, it's my whole *gift.* But I can't dismiss a *request to simply look at the person.* *(he nods, slowly, the certainty not gone but *humbled.*)* You're right. Whatever I decide — yes, or no — I owe it to her, and to *myself*, to decide it *looking at a face* and not *reading a proof.* If the Wall is *just*, I should be able to vote for it while *meeting her eyes.* And if I *can't* meet her eyes and still raise my hand — *(his voice drops)* — then it was never *just*, and my *airtight* logic was only a way to *vote without seeing.* *(he straightens, young and grave.)* I'll go to the dock. I'll look at Maerys. And *then* I'll decide what my hand does. That's — that's the most *honest* thing anyone's asked of me since I put on these robes. Thank you, stranger. I was about to vote with my *eyes closed* and call it *clarity.*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "npc.young_ilfaeril_face", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act3.ilfaeril_asks", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act1.mercy_remembered", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "companion.ilfaeril.approval", op = FlagOp.AddInt, amount = 4 } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "loyal", speaker = "Ilfaeril, the Younger",
                text = "*(He pulls back, the young pride reasserting like a reflex.)* No — you're trying to make me *doubt*, and *doubt* is what my elders *warned* me about. *(he lifts his chin.)* The logic *is* airtight. I *checked* it. And a judge who lets a *stranger's riddles* unmake a *proof* on the eve of his *first vote* is no judge at all. *(but his hand, you notice, has curled slightly, uncertain.)* The Coronal is *wise.* My elders are *wise.* They cannot *all* be wrong, and I — I am *eighteen*, and *brilliant*, and I will not *throw away* their faith in me for a *feeling.* *(he turns toward the voting chamber.)* I vote *yes.* With a *whole heart.* As I *planned.* *(and he goes, certain and clear-eyed and proud, toward the hand-raising that will take him ten thousand years to understand — and you realize, with a chill, that you may have just watched the exact moment your companion's grief was born.)*",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
                onEnter = new[] { new FlagClause { key = "npc.young_ilfaeril_votes_yes", op = FlagOp.SetTrue }, new FlagClause { key = "act3.ilfaeril_raises_hand", op = FlagOp.SetTrue } },
            });

            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "close", speaker = "Ilfaeril, the Younger",
                text = "*(The young judge moves toward his first vote — brilliant, certain, ten thousand years away from the grief that will hollow and deepen and finally *redeem* him — and whether his hand rose or stayed down, you carry out of that founding chamber the strangest grief of all: that you have looked your ancient, sorrowing companion in his *young* face, on the worst and most innocent day of his life, and seen exactly where the wound began.)*",
            });

            NpcCrownIlfaerilDialogue = g;
        }
    }
}
